I only had about 3 weeks of "all in" on the $180 billion or more bucket. This was based on the GRAB spac that I thought would add $40bn to the pot. It didn't, so here we are.
Returned to high on bucket 3...
It seems I massively misunderstood gross proceeds, and Grab will only bring 4.5 bn, not ~40 ish... this one is going to hurt...

Inline with what @pstance has said, I think what matters is when the original SPAC raised money and not when it lists. The gross proceeds can only be either the amount raised by Altimeter Growth when it went public or the amount raised by the company it acquired which is $4.5bn. I think the former interpretation makes more sense. I should have clarified this before jumping to conclusions!
After reading the post by @pstance, I'm second-guessing my previous assumptions, so I'm going back to the crowd's odds until I get a better grasp of the situation with Grab.

I think there is some confusion as to what gross proceeds mean. Gross proceeds on SPACs are generated when a SPAC goes public, not when a SPAC merges with a private company. Thus, Grab's merger with Altimeter Growth Corp. does not generate any gross proceeds. Those proceeds were had when Altimeter went public in December of 2020.

Updating my prediction based on slowing SPAC IPO listings.

With the wind heavily out of the sails there has still been an additional 1B in activity over the last 2 weeks (just over 105b currently). With that in mind, and 29 weeks left in the year, and with a few potentially large SPAC's in the wings, it seems more than likely to cross the $140b mark but heavily dependent on outliers to cross 180b (ie. Robinhood). It would realistically only take one or two of these to push past 180b and there is active work being done to work around the new rules (https://financialpost.com/pmn/business-pmn/wall-street-grapples-with-new-spac-equity-contracts-after-regulator-crackdown). The 85% drop in activity in April/May vs the first quarter is unlikely to last and probably more indicative of learning how to work with the new rules. I'm betting it will be a few more months before activity really picks up again but the incentives are huge so I believe its more a matter of when than if. I'll dial back 5% from 89% over 180b until there is more news, or a major transaction.

Adjusting my estimate down from 100% "$180 billion or more" given the slowing SPAC listings. Per Bloomberg, SPACs are facing increased investor scrutiny and, more importantly, SEC regulatory hurdles (https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-03-31/spac-listings-slow-to-a-crawl-with-bankers-buried-in-paperwork). From the article: "The SEC’s processing of SPAC documentation is taking longer than it previously did. In some cases, agency staff have warned lawyers that it may take a full 30 days to review paperwork and to expect an additional two weeks to hear back on changes or amendments."

Reposting link from @John-Baker ( https://spacinsider.com/stats/ ). SPAC IPOs fell of the cliff in April (~2.6B since April 6th based on @John-Baker data below ). It's unlikely they are going to resume much if at all. Most SPACs are trading below IPO prices and even the deal announcements do not bring much of a pop. There are 267 SPACs that applied for IPOs, but I doubt even half of them will IPO. This market is dead. It might not even get above 140B.

There is some feeling abroad in the land that new accounting rules and practices might put the brakes on this market pretty fast. It may be useful to remember that "pretty fast" in the world of business regulation can mean anything from a couple of months to a couple of years, but I think I'll bump it down a little bit as a substitute for thinking too hard about it.

As of today, April 6, SpacInsider (https://spacinsider.com/stats/) reports 2021 SPAC dollars totaling $97.4 billion on 299 transactions. Thus, in only 3 full months, gross proceeds from SPAC IPO transactions are already more than half way to the $180 billion benchmark. A simple linear prediction would put the 2021 total closer to $360 billion.

Mergers through blank-check companies are an increasingly growing share of the M&A market, with first-quarter volume already exceeding that seen in all of 2020.
Mergers through blank-check companies are an increasingly growing share of the M&A market, with first-quarter volume already exceeding that seen in all of 2020.

The first quarter is barely over, and the number of IPOs (275 "Searching"+ 1 "Announced" already exceeds 2020 total. There's a total of 219 IPOs (a leftover of 6 "Filed for IPO" of 2020 + 213 this year) IPOs already in the pipeline. More is likely to come, and even in times of rocky stock markets, the frenzy could continue due to a favorable structure (taxes? liquidity?). The structure likely also allows smaller and younger companies that are probably not mature enough for a conventional IPO to go public (ownership change) and/or stock owners to cash out, and even probably lowers the cost of going public relative to their market cap. I consider at least 600 IPOs for the full year of 2021 to be perfectly possible. The average IPO size had its erstwhile peak in 2020, and shrank to 325mn on average so far in 2021, but as long as it exceeds 300mn in the end, gross proceeds will exceed 180mn USD.
